ence.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|''[[Wolfenstein (2009 video game)|Wolfenstein]]''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence and Nazi references.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|''[[Wolfenstein 3D]]''\n|Originally banned because of Nazi references. The ban has been overturned in 2019 on grounds of social adequacy.\n|-\n|''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]] (PS3, Xbox 360, PC)''\n|Banned because of high-impact gory violence.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|}\n\n==Greece==\n{{see also|Law 3037/2002}}\nNo known games have been banned in [[Greece]]. A law banning ''all'' electronic games in public places was passed in 2002, but eventually disregarded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/2100-1040-956357.html|title=In Greece, use a GameBoy, go to jail|last1=Goodwins|first1=Rupert|date=2002-09-02|website=[[CNet]]|accessdate=2014-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714120441/http://news.cnet.com/2100-1040-956357.html|archive-date=2014-07-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/2238242.stm|title=Greeks fight computer game ban|date=2002-09-05|work=BBC News|accessdate=2014-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305234852/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/2238242.stm|archive-date=2014-03-05|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/greek-game-ban-overturned/125096|title=Greek game ban overturned|last1=Loney|first1=Matt|date=2002-10-11|website=ZDNet|accessdate=2014-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326002333/http://www.zdnet.com/news/greek-game-ban-overturned/125096|archive-date=2014-03-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\nMany games were censored in Greece, such as GTA 4 in 2010 when the Greek government claimed the game was full of extreme gore and even referenced a scene where one of the characters, Jimmy Pegorino, killed a couple. Half-Life 2 was also pulled off the shelves in Greek video game stores in 2006, due to its dystopian setting.\nIn 2018, Fortnite was banned in Crete, causing massive controversy amon many Greek teens, as the game was popular. This did not affect the digital sales of the game.\n\n==India==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[PUBG Mobile]]''\n|Temporarily banned because of extreme violence. The move came after a direction from [[Gujarat]] and [[Jammu and Kashmir]] state department seeking a ban on the game, as it was claimed to affect the minds of youths who tend to become violent<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/technology/news/story/pubg-mobile-makes-player-go-mad-admitted-to-hospital-under-serious-trauma-1427705-2019-01-10</ref> and banned in [[Jammu and kashmir]] because people of [[Jammu and Kashmir]] have playing PUBG for 10 days without resting and got sick get banned a 6-hour ban<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/now-pubg-banned-in-city/articleshow/68399514.cms|title=Now, PUBG banned in city|last=Mar 14|first=Ahmedabad Mirror {{!}} Updated|last2=2019|website=Ahmedabad Mirror|language=en|access-date=2019-03-15|last3=Ist|first3=06:16}}</ref> The game was banned in [[Gujarat]], in the cities of [[Ahmedabad]], [[Surat]], [[Vadodara]], [[Bhavnagar]] And [[Rajkot]] and [[Jammu and Kashmir]], but only for the mobile version.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/tech/pubg-mobile-ban-you-will-get-arrested-for-playing-the-battle-royal-game-in-these-cities-in-india-2066153.html|title=PUBG Mobile Ban: You Will Get Arrested For Playing The Battle Royal Game in These Cities in India|website=News18|access-date=2019-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331171414/https://www.news18.com/news/tech/pubg-mobile-ban-you-will-get-arrested-for-playing-the-battle-royal-game-in-these-cities-in-india-2066153.html|archive-date=2019-03-31|url-status=live}}</ref> PC and console versions remained unaffected of ban.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/578080/PLAYERUNKNOWNS_BATTLEGROUNDS/|title=PLAYERUNKNOWN'S BATTLEGROUNDS on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507085804/https://store.steampowered.com/app/578080/PLAYERUNKNOWNS_BATTLEGROUNDS/|archive-date=2019-05-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n|-\n| ''[[Dungeon Hunter 5]]''\n| Banned because of high graphic violence in [[Dharmanagar]] and [[Panisagar]]. The [[Dungeon Hunter 5]] mobile version is also banned.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/1255814-breves |title=Breves \u2013 Alertan por el riesgo de un videojuego |date=19 April 2010 |access-date=30 July 2018 |work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]] |language=Bengali |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730203250/https://www.lanacion.com.ar/1255814-breves |archive-date=2018-07-30 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5520973/years-later-argentina-bans-rape-video-game|title=Years Later, Argentina Bans Rape Video Game|last1=Ashcraft|first1=Brian|date=21 April 2010|website=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=30 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730234744/https://kotaku.com/5520973/years-later-argentina-bans-rape-video-game|archive-date=2018-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Iran==\n{{Main|Censorship in Iran}}\nIran typically bans any game that contains violence, depicts cruelty, features strong sexual content, nudity, or portrays the Middle East negatively.\n''[[Battlefield 3]]'' was banned because it presented a fictional U.S. invasion on [[Tehran]]. Even before the ban, many retail stores were removing copies of the game from their shelves.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jCwtm31oYnU70sTJKF8iltAfNHnA?docId=CNG.8af6b7bf5835350c0f276c56855993c1.201 | title=Iran bans US video game showing Tehran invasion | publisher=AFP | date=Nov 28, 2011 | access-date=2018-10-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225212856/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jCwtm31oYnU70sTJKF8iltAfNHnA?docId=CNG.8af6b7bf5835350c0f276c56855993c1.201 | archive-date=2012-02-25 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]'' was banned due to security reasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pokemon Go banned by Iranian authorities over 'security'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-36989526|website=[[BBC]]|accessdate=2016-10-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917044204/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-36989526|archive-date=2016-09-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]'' was banned for excessively glorifying homosexual and immoral values. The ban does not extend to digital distribution, however.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=ir|title=VALKYRIE DRIVE -BHIKKHUNI- on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017224315/https://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=ir|archive-date=2018-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Republic of Ireland==\n{{main|Video gaming in the Republic of Ireland}}\n\nThe [[Irish Film Classification Office|IFCO]] rarely rates video games, and leaves decisions to [[Pan European Game Information|PEGI]] and the [[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]]. ''[[Manhunt 2]]'' was banned for \"gross, unrelenting, and gratuitous violence\", but the ban was later lifted and the game was given a PEGI 18 rating.<ref>[http://www.ifco.ie/ifco/ifcoweb.nsf/web/news?opendocument&news=yes&type=graphic \"Manhunt 2 Video Game Prohibited.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071120192726/http://www.ifco.ie/ifco/ifcoweb.nsf/web/news?opendocument&news=yes&type=graphic |date=2007-11-20 }} Irish Film Classification Office.</ref>\n\n==Italy==\nIn 2006, following the release of the trailer to the game ''[[Rule of Rose]]'', the magazine ''[[Panorama (magazine)|Panorama]]'' ran an article claiming live burials of children at the protagonist's hand. Shortly after, then-mayor of [[Rome]], [[Walter Veltroni]], called for a ban of the game in Italy. The game's European publisher, [[505 Games]], dismissed these claims,<ref name=\"Rule\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news171106ruleofrose|title=505 Games responds to Rule of Rose controversy|author=GamesIndustry International|date=17 November 2006|publisher=Eurogamer.net|access-date=24 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625050518/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news171106ruleofrose|archive-date=2018-06-25|url-status=live}}</ref> and the game was not banned following Veltroni's comments.\n\nIn 2007, following the decision of the governments of the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], the Minister of Communications [[Paolo Gentiloni]] publicly expressed the desire to ban the distribution of ''[[Manhunt 2]]'' in Italy, due to the gratuitous violence and excessive cruelty in the video game, but the ban was never put into practice.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://punto-informatico.it/2024293/PI/News/censura-gentiloni-blocca-manhunt.aspx |title=Censura, Gentiloni blocca Manhunt 2 |last1=Maruccia |first1=Alfonso |language=Italian |date=22 June 2007 |publisher=[[Punto Informatico]] |accessdate=11 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111235414/http://punto-informatico.it/2024293/PI/News/censura-gentiloni-blocca-manhunt.aspx |archive-date=2013-11-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Japan==\n{{main|\nVideo games in Japan}}\n\nVideo games are rarely banned in Japan, and it holds the place as one of the top video game producers in the world.<ref>[http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/features/arts/20081017TDY12001.htm \"Game over? Not yet: Japan's video game industry appears vibrant despite a crisis of confidence\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019122741/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/features/arts/20081017TDY12001.htm |date=2008-10-19 }} Daily Yomiuri Online.</ref> However, ''[[Fallout 3]]'' was edited in Japan due to two reasons: a quest named \"The Power of the Atom\" which gave the player a choice to nuke a city named Megaton, which caused part of the quest to be removed, and a weapon in the game called the [[Fat Man]]. Because of its relation to the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|real historic event]], the weapon was renamed to the Nuka Launcher in the Japanese version of ''Fallout 3''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://games.uk.msn.com/gaming/photos/photos.aspx?cp-documentid=155028519&page=2 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606014629/http://games.uk.msn.com/gaming/photos/photos.aspx?cp-documentid=155028519&page=2 |archive-date=2013-06-06 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref> Japan's [[Spike (company)|Spike]] removed all references to [[Kim Jong-il]] and [[North Korea]] in ''[[Homefront (video game)|Homefront]]'', as well.<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker |first=Laura |url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/action/homefront/news.html?sid=6297959 |title=Kim Jong-il axed from Homefront in Japan |publisher=Gamespot.com |date=2011-03-15 |accessdate=2011-10-26}}</ref> ''[[Resident Evil 4]]'', ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops]]'', ''[[Bulletstorm]]'', ''[[Gears of War 3]]'', ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]'', ''[[Dead Island]]'', ''[[Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance]]'' and numerous other violent titles{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}, distributed physically and digitally, were heavily edited for excessive violence, but only on the localization level; the games can still be played if the locale is switched from Japanese to English. The ''[[Mortal Kombat]]'' series was subsequently banned in Japan, including its newest release, due to heavy amounts of violence {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}. On 13 March 2019, the sales of ''[[Judgement (video game)|Judgement]]'' had stopped producing future sales in Japan, following [[Pierre Taki]]'s arrest on suspicion of cocaine use. As a result, [[Sega]] had replaced both the voice actor and the character model having been subsequently removed.\n\n==Kenya==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]''\n|Banned because of sexual content and glorification of homosexuality. The ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=ke|title=VALKYRIE DRIVE -BHIKKHUNI- on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Malaysia==\n{{main|Video gaming in Malaysia}}\nMalaysia tends to ban offensive content such as extreme impact violence, depictions of cruelty, any content considered [[Criticism of Islam|anti-Muslim]], sexual content and nudity. In August 2008, after the ''Grand Theft Auto'' series ban in Thailand ([[List of banned video games#Thailand|see below]]), head of a Malaysian consumer rights organization, Muhammad Idris, called for the ban of the entire [[Grand Theft Auto|''Grand Theft Auto'' series]] and other similarly violent video games such as the [[Manhunt (video game series)|''Manhunt'' series]] and ''[[Mortal Kombat]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.malaysianbar.org.my/legal/general_news/fomca_regulate_video_games.html |title=Fomca: Regulate video games |publisher=Malaysianbar.org.my |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2011-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610205540/http://www.malaysianbar.org.my/legal/general_news/fomca_regulate_video_games.html |archive-date=2011-06-10 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/malaysian-consumer-group-blame-it-all-on-gta-98824.phtml|title=Malaysian Consumer Group blame it all on GTA|last=Bennett|first=Colette|website=Destructoid|access-date=2010-01-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211200420/http://www.destructoid.com/malaysian-consumer-group-blame-it-all-on-gta-98824.phtml|archive-date=2010-02-11|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2010, one week after ''[[Dante's Inferno (video game)|Dante's Inferno]]'' was released, the game was banned by Jabatan Agama Islam (JAIS) in Malaysia for offensive depictions of cruelty, hellish visions, sexuality and content that was against [[Sharia]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\nIn 2016, ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]'' was banned by the Federal Territory for Muslims for promoting the search for power, which leads to gambling and safety issues related to playing the game. The ban was later lifted following massive backlash on social media and an update that slightly modified security measures on the app.\n\nIn September 2017, the [[Malaysian Communications and Multimedia Commission]] (MCMC) blocked access to the entire Steam store following the discovery of a controversial fighting game involving religious deities, Fight of Gods.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lowyat.net/2017/140309/fighting-game-featuring-jesus-buddha-receives-condemnation-religious-leaders/|title=MCMC Blocks Entire Steam Store Following God Fighting Game Controversy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028152423/https://www.lowyat.net/2017/140309/fighting-game-featuring-jesus-buddha-receives-condemnation-religious-leaders/|archive-date=2017-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban was lifted one day later after Valve agreed to block the game in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lowyat.net/2017/140631/mcmc-unblocks-steam-offending-game-geoblocked/|title=MCMC Unblocks Steam After Offending Game Geoblocked|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108215740/https://www.lowyat.net/2017/140631/mcmc-unblocks-steam-offending-game-geoblocked/|archive-date=2017-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Mexico==\nThough no video games have ever been banned in the country, ''[[Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon Advanced Warfighter 2]]'' was banned in the state of [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] due to Mexican rebels being depicted as antagonists and stereotyping the cities of [[Chihuahua City]] and [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]].<ref name=\"MEX-GRAW2\">{{cite web|last=Gaudiosi|first=John|work=WRAL News|date=2007-03-26|title=Locally-made \"GRAW2\" Banned in Mexico|url=http://www.wral.com/entertainment/blogpost/1248223/|publisher=wral.com|accessdate=2007-03-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070329014914/http://www.wral.com/entertainment/blogpost/1248223/|archivedate=2007-03-29}}</ref> However, the game can still be found in shelves in other states.\n\n==Nepal==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[PUBG]]''\n|Banned because of delinquency issues involving youths.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/12/18308618/pubg-ban-nepal-violence-video-game-addiction |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-04-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415004118/https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/12/18308618/pubg-ban-nepal-violence-video-game-addiction |archive-date=2019-04-15 |url-status=live }}</ref> At present, the ban has been lifted<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/578080/PLAYERUNKNOWNS_BATTLEGROUNDS/?cc=np|title=PLAYERUNKNOWN'S BATTLEGROUNDS on Steam|last=|first=|date=|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==New Zealand==\n{{main|Video gaming in New Zealand}}\nIn [[New Zealand]], games are classified by the [[Office of Film and Literature Classification (New Zealand)|country's Office of Film and Literature Classification]]. If they are dubbed \"objectionable\" in all cases, they are banned. In this case, the game in question is not only illegal to sell, but also to own, possess, or import. Games are typically banned and classified as \"objectionable content\" when they contain extreme violence, offensive depictions of cruelty, animal cruelty, sexual content involving children, or graphic depictions of sexual content, including sexual fetishes that are \"offensive & abhorrent\" (depictions of urination, [[bestiality]], [[necrophilia]], [[urophilia]], [[coprophilia]], and/or [[incest]]).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[Criminal Girls: Invite Only]]''\n|Banned because of sexual content that focuses on young persons and elements of sexual violence.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.classificationoffice.govt.nz/news/classification-decision-snapshots |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127191516/https://www.classificationoffice.govt.nz/news/classification-decision-snapshots |archive-date=2018-01-27 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Gal*Gun: Double Peace]]''\n| Banned because \"it tends to promote and support both the exploitation of children and young people, and the use of [[coercion]] to compel a person to submit to sexual conduct\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fvlb.org.nz/nz/pages/publication-details.html?title=199675 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131190923/http://www.fvlb.org.nz/nz/pages/publication-details.html?title=199675 |archive-date=2017-01-31 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Manhunt (video game)|Manhunt]]''\n| Banned because of graphic violence and depictions of cruelty.<ref>[http://www.censorship.govt.nz/PDFWORD/manhunt.pdf Manhunt: Reasons for Decision] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070203011642/http://www.censorship.govt.nz/PDFWORD/manhunt.pdf |date=3 February 2007 }}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Manhunt 2]]''\n|Banned because of graphic violence and depictions of cruelty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nzgamer.com/news/2660/manhunt-2-banned-in-nz.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-06-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123091531/http://nzgamer.com/news/2660/manhunt-2-banned-in-nz.html |archive-date=2016-01-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Postal 2]]'' \n| Banned because of \"Gross, abhorrent content: Urination, High Impact Violence, Animal Cruelty, Homophobia, Racial, and Ethnic Stereotypes\u201d.<ref>''[https://www.geek.com/games/11-video-games-that-got-banned-and-why-1645406/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127045508/https://www.geek.com/games/11-video-games-that-got-banned-and-why-1645406/ |date=27 January 2019 }}'' By K. Thor Jensen 08.11.2018 :: 2:00PM EST kthorjensen.</ref>\n|-\n|-\n|''[[RapeLay]]''\n|Banned because it \"tends to promote and support the use of violence to compel a person to submit to sexual conduct, and the exploitation of young persons for sexual purposes\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n|-\n| ''[[Reservoir Dogs (video game)|Reservoir Dogs]]''\n| Banned because it \"tends to promote and support the infliction of extreme violence and extreme cruelty for the purpose of entertainment\".<ref>{{cite press release|title=Reservoir Dogs Computer Game Banned|publisher=New Zealand Office of Film and Literature Classification|date=2006-07-07|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO0607/S00059.htm|accessdate=2006-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716092216/http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO0607/S00059.htm|archive-date=2006-07-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Three Sisters' Story]]''\n| Banned because it \"tends to promote and support the use of violence to compel a person to submit to sexual conduct, and the exploitation of young persons for sexual purposes\".{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n|-\n| ''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]''\n| Banned because it \"tends to promote and support incest between the two lead focal sisters, and the exploitation of young persons for sexual purposes\".{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|}\n<!-- Please verify if playing such games is banned as well, but be sure to cite reliable sources! -->\n\n==North Korea==\nNorth Korea bans all foreign video games (regardless of content) and very few games are known to be developed in North Korea.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]''\n|Banned because of the presence of gambling in GTA Online. Gambling of any kind is banned in North Korea.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n|-\n|[[Homefront (video game)|''Homefront'']]\n|Banned because of its negative portrayal of a unified Korea under Northern rule.<ref name=\"ZDNet Korea\"/>\n|}\n\n==Pakistan==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason \n|-\n|''[[Medal of Honor: Warfighter]]''\n\n| Banned for portraying Pakistanis negatively.<ref name=\"COD&MOH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2013/01/23/black-ops-2-warfighter-banned-in-pakistan-for-depicting-country/|title=Black Ops 2, Warfighter banned in Pakistan for depicting country in 'very poor light'|date=2013-01-23|website=Joystiq|last1=Conditt|first1=Jessica|accessdate=2014-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126101228/http://www.joystiq.com/2013/01/23/black-ops-2-warfighter-banned-in-pakistan-for-depicting-country|archive-date=2013-01-26|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/202970/Call_of_Duty_Black_Ops_II/?cc=pk|title=Call of Duty\u00ae: Black Ops II on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Postal 2]]''\n| Banned because of violence against Muslims who are portrayed as terrorists. The ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n|-\n| ''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]''\n| Banned because of sexual content and glorifying homosexuality. However, the ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=pk|title=VALKYRIE DRIVE -BHIKKHUNI- on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020214004/https://store.steampowered.com/app/550080/VALKYRIE_DRIVE_BHIKKHUNI/?cc=pk|archive-date=2018-10-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[https://g.co/kgs/p4xexy Negligee: Love Stories]\n|Banned for sexual content and glorifying homosexuality.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} The ban does not extend to digital versions of the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/1002100/Negligee_Love_Stories/?cc=pk|title=Negligee: Love Stories on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Philippines==\n{{main|Video gaming in the Philippines}}\nIn 1981, a presidential decree issued by [[Ferdinand Marcos]] outlawed the use and distribution<ref name=\"Long\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/11/1119marcos-bans-videogames-philippines/|title=Nov. 19, 1981: Marcos Regime Puts the Kibosh on Games|last=Long|first=Tony|date=19 November 2010|work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|accessdate=26 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226052812/http://www.wired.com/2010/11/1119marcos-bans-videogames-philippines/|archive-date=2015-02-26|url-status=live}}</ref> of ''all'' video game consoles, arcade games and pinball machines, deeming them as a \"destructive social enemy\"<ref>{{cite news|title=President Marcos bans video game machines|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/10056192/?terms=marcos+video+games|newspaper=Logansport Pharos-Tribune|date=19 November 1981|page=17|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate=26 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320055905/http://www.newspapers.com/image/10056192/?terms=marcos+video+games|archive-date=2015-03-20|url-status=live}} {{Open access}}</ref> and \"to the detriment of the public interest\".<ref name=\"PD519\">{{cite web|url=http://source.gosupra.com/docs/provision/78753|title=Presidential Decree No. 519 - Supra Source|accessdate=26 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107151855/http://source.gosupra.com/docs/provision/78753|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Dillon|first=Roberto|title=The Golden Age of Video Games: The Birth of a Multibillion Dollar Industry|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1439873232|date=12 April 2011|publisher=CRC Press|location=Page xvii|isbn=978-1439873236}}</ref> Despite the law being technically in effect following the [[EDSA Revolution]], it has since been disregarded and unenforced.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nWhile no video games are banned nationwide so far since 1986, at least one title, ''[[Defense of the Ancients]]'', has been banned at a [[barangay]] in [[Dasmari\u00f1as, Cavite]] following complaints of [[Juvenile delinquency|delinquency]] issues, and two murder incidents involving youths in the area resulting from brawls in relation to the game.<ref name=\"DOTABan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/413042/news/regions/dota-banned-in-internet-shops-in-cavite-village|title=DOTA banned in internet shops in Cavite village|date=21 January 2015|work=[[GMA News]]|accessdate=27 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065934/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/413042/news/regions/dota-banned-in-internet-shops-in-cavite-village|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Russia==\nIn [[Russia]], games are classified by the \"[[On Protecting Children from Information Harmful to Their Health and Development]]\" federal law. No known games have been banned in Russia due to excessive violence, nudity, negative portrayal of people of Russia or expression of religious views of any kind because of the freedom of speech guaranteed by the [[Constitution of Russia]]. Media in the [[United States]] and [[Europe]] have incorrectly reported that ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2]]'', which features a storyline in which Russian \"[[ultranationalists]]\" take control of the country and invade the United States, was banned in Russia. Activision called these reports 'erroneous'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/video-games/6588218/Call-Of-Duty-Modern-Warfare-2-not-banned-in-Russia-says-Activision.html|title=Call Of Duty: Modern Warfare 2 not banned in Russia, says Activision|last=Cowen|first=Nick|date=2009-11-17|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=21 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020080012/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/video-games/6588218/Call-Of-Duty-Modern-Warfare-2-not-banned-in-Russia-says-Activision.html|archive-date=2010-10-20|location=London|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Sony Interactive Entertainment Russia refused to sell ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare (2019 video game)|Call of Duty: Modern Warfare]]'' digitally.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n| ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare (2019 video game)|Call of Duty: Modern Warfare]]''\n| Not officially banned, but Sony Interactive Entertainment refused to sell the game digitally on PlayStation 4.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dexerto.com/call-of-duty/call-of-duty-modern-warfare-banned-russian-playstation-store-1171401 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-10-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022182738/https://www.dexerto.com/call-of-duty/call-of-duty-modern-warfare-banned-russian-playstation-store-1171401 |archive-date=2019-10-22 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Saudi Arabia==\n<!-- Please verify if playing such games is banned as well, but be sure to cite reliable sources! -->\n\nMost banned games can be found in many stores (often at a substantial price) due to the government failing to enforce the bans of these games. However, some major stores will not stock banned titles.<ref>http://www.gcam.gov.sa/ar/AboutGcam/AgeClassification/Pages/AgeClassificationList.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616030323/http://www.gcam.gov.sa/ar/AboutGcam/AgeClassification/Pages/AgeClassificationList.aspx |date=2018-06-16 }} (Only Arabic Texture)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gcam.gov.sa/ar/AboutGcam/AgeClassification/Pages/AgeClassificationList.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616030323/http://www.gcam.gov.sa/ar/AboutGcam/AgeClassification/Pages/AgeClassificationList.aspx |archive-date=2018-06-16 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!Name\n!Reason\n|-\n|''[[God of War (franchise)]]''\n| Banned for a few weeks due to the presence of interactive sex scenes, partial nudity, and sexual themes, as well as the word \"God\" in the title. In 2018, the newest game in the series was approved for release.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Call of Duty 4: Modern Warfare]]''\n|Banned for a few weeks because of role-playing the Middle East as terrorists.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Assassin's Creed]]''\n|Banned for two weeks because of a perceived negative portrayal of Arabs. Later completely banned due to its use in the Blue Whale Challenge.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n|-\n|''[[Grand Theft Auto (series)]]''\n|Banned for extreme impact violence and nudity.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Heavy Rain]]''\n|Banned because of high impact violence, nudity, and a sex scene.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[L.A. Noire]]''\n|Banned because of extreme impact violence and nudity.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Postal 2]]''\n|Banned because of extreme impact violence, nudity and the portrayal of Muslims as terrorists.\n|-\n|''[[Red Dead Redemption]]''\n|Banned due to nudity, prostitution, violence, and cruelty.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Red Dead Redemption 2]]''\n|Banned due to nudity, prostitution, violence, and cruelty.\n|-\n|''[[Manhunt (video game series)]]'' (all versions)\n|Banned because of low impact scary violence and cruelty.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|- \n|''[[Manhunt 2]]''\n|Banned for \"gross, unrelenting, and gratuitous violence\".{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[South Park: The Stick of Truth]]/[[South Park: The Fractured but Whole|The Fractured but Whole]]'' (all versions)\n| Banned because of extremely offensive content.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n|-\n|''[[Valkyrie Drive: Bhikkhuni]]'' \n| Banned due to sexual content and excessive themes of glorifying homosexuality.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n|-\n|''[[Wolfenstein (series)|Wolfenstein]]'' \n| Banned because of the presence of interactive sex scenes.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n|-\n|''[[Metro (series)]]'' \n| Banned due to its use in the Blue Whale Challenge.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n|-\n|''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]''\n|Banned because of the presence of sex scenes.\n|-\n|''[[Watch Dogs (series)]]''\n|Banned due to frequent use of sexual expletives, sexual activity with visible genitals and the motiveless killing of innocent human characters.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n|}\n\n==Singapore==\n[[Singapore]] rarely bans games. With the implementation of the Video Game Classification in 2008 by the [[Media Development Authority]], most games are widely available for purchase to their respective age group, such as those containing full frontal nudity or strong graphic violence under an \"M18\" rating. Games that were previously banned such as [[Mass Effect]] were re-rated either \"Age Advisory\" or \"M18\" after the implementation of the classification system.\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!Name\n!Reason\n|-\n|''[[Half-Life (video game)|Half-Life]]''\n|Banned because of violence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore Bans Half-Life|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/singapore-bans-half-life/1100-2446255/|publisher=Gamespot|date=24 January 2000|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160523174058/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/singapore-bans-half-life/1100-2446255/|archive-date=2016-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref>  The ban was met with uproar as the local gaming community and retailers scrambled to start petitions to save the game. The government decided to lift the ban after a week, as the game had been released for more than a year and the ban would impact the local LAN gaming and retail market.<ref>{{cite web|title=Half-Life ban lifted|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/half-life-ban-lifted/1100-2446436/|publisher=Gamespot|date=3 February 2000|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107151856/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/half-life-ban-lifted/1100-2446436/|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Mass Effect]]''\n|Banned because of a homosexual encounter between a feminine alien and female human.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory?id=3872709 \"Singapore Bans Game Over Lesbian Scene.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226002102/http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory?id=3872709 |date=2009-02-26 }} ABC News.</ref> The ban was later lifted and the title re-rated M18.<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10476791\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/location/story.cfm?l_id=3&objectid=10476791 |title=Ban lifted on Xbox game with sex scene |date=18 November 2007 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |agency=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=14 October 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Darkness (video game)|The Darkness]]''\n|Banned because of excessive violence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameaxis.com/home/?blog=1558 |title=The Darkness - Banned in Singapore (Game Axis) |access-date=2007-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215001649/http://www.gameaxis.com/home/?blog=1558 |archive-date=2007-12-15 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ban was later lifted and the title re-rated M18.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n|}\n<!-- Please verify if playing such games is banned as well, but be sure to cite reliable sources! -->\n\n==South Korea==\n{{see also|Video gaming in South Korea}}\nSince 2006, South Korea offers complete freedom in publishing games, fully respecting freedom of expression and speech. Even before this, games were very rarely banned unless that game mentioned elements of the [[Korean War]] in order to avoid tensions between the [[North Korea]] and [[South Korea]]. However, ''[[Manhunt (video game)|Manhunt]]'', ''[[Manhunt 2]]'', and ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]'' are still banned because of violence and cruelty. ''[[Grand Theft Auto III]]'', ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City]]'' and ''[[Mercenaries: Playground of Destruction]]'' were previously banned, but the bans were later lifted.<ref>''[http://www.gamespot.com/news/6163609.html Korea lifts game censorship] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070827022848/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6163609.html |date=2007-08-27 }}'' by Emma Boyes, 2006-12-29, [[GameSpot]]</ref>\n\nThe [[Game Rating Board]] requires that all video games be rated by the organization. Unrated titles are absolutely banned from being sold in the country, and websites selling them can be blocked.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n|[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|''Mortal Kombat'' (2011)]]\n|Banned because of excessive violence and cruelty.<ref name=\"ZDNet Korea\">{{cite news|url=http://www.zdnet.co.kr/news/news_view.asp?artice_id=20110407102001|script-title=ko:\uc131\uc778 \uac8c\uc784 \ubaa8\ud0c8\ucef4\ubc43, \uc2ec\uc758 '\uac70\ubd80'\u2026\uc5ed\uc2dc \uc794\uc778\ud574\uc11c?|date=2011-04-07|work=[[ZDNet|ZDNet Korea]]|language=ja|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023060034/http://www.zdnet.co.kr/news/news_view.asp?artice_id=20110407102001|archive-date=2013-10-23|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Homefront (video game)|''Homefront'']]\n|Banned because of its negative portrayal of a unified Korea under Northern rule.<ref name=\"ZDNet Korea\"/>\n|-\n|[[Danganronpa V3: Killing Harmony|''Danganronpa V3'']]\n|The September 2017 release was cancelled because of a <!-- how recent? -->case in South Korea where a 17-year-old girl killed and dismembered an 8-year-old child.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} The game was banned to prevent controversies.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n|}\n<!-- Please verify if playing such games was banned as well, but be sure to cite reliable sources! -->\n\n==Thailand==\n[[Thailand]] will typically ban any games with excessive violence, and sexual content, such as many [[eroge]] from Japan, for the same reasons as its ban on any pornographic films.\n\nAdditionally, since August 2008, all video game titles of the ''[[Grand Theft Auto]]'' series have been completely banned in Thailand,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thainn.com/exchange/temp_news.php?type1=1&type2=4&page=0&topic=5346&view=0 |title=\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e48\u0e07\u0e41\u0e1a\u0e19GTA \u0e23\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e40\u0e01\u0e21\u0e44\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e21\u0e35\u0e42\u0e14\u0e19\u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a |accessdate=2009-08-09 |date=2008-08-06 |work=[[Daily News (Thailand)|Daily News]] |publisher=ThaiNN.com |language=th |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817095730/http://www.thainn.com/exchange/temp_news.php?type1=1&type2=4&page=0&topic=5346&view=0 |archive-date=2008-08-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> because of a case where an 18-year-old Thai player supposedly influenced by ''Grand Theft Auto'' killed a taxi driver from Bangkok.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sanook.com/crime/crime_293428.php? |title=\u0e2a\u0e25\u0e14! \u0e21.6 \u0e41\u0e17\u0e07\u0e42\u0e2b\u0e14\u0e06\u0e48\u0e32\u0e41\u0e17\u0e47\u0e01\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e40\u0e25\u0e35\u0e22\u0e19\u0e41\u0e1a\u0e1a\u0e40\u0e01\u0e21\u0e42\u0e08\u0e23 GTA |accessdate=2009-08-09 |date=2008-08-04 |work=[[Thai Rath]] |publisher=Sanook.com |language=th |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331191217/http://news.sanook.com/crime/crime_293428.php |archive-date=2009-03-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe ban, however, does not extend to the digital PC versions of [[Grand Theft Auto V]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/271590/Grand_Theft_Auto_V/?cc=th|title=Grand Theft Auto V on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302090814/https://store.steampowered.com/app/271590/Grand_Theft_Auto_V/?cc=th|archive-date=2019-03-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Tropico 5]] is yet another banned title. The military junta claims that it could \"affect peace and order\" within the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/tropico-5-banned-in-thailand-because-it-could-affe/1100-6421473/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801094320/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/tropico-5-banned-in-thailand-because-it-could-affe/1100-6421473/ |archive-date=2018-08-01 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n\n==United Arab Emirates==\n<!--- TO DO: get sources for games with unknown reasons --->\nIn the [[United Arab Emirates]], a branch of the government called the [[National Media Council (United Arab Emirates)|National Media Council]] (NMC) works to control the media and entertainment industry in the country, and they have the authority to issue bans on any specific media products, including video games, to comply with the country's legal and cultural values. Usually, the NMC do not explicitly state their actual consensus for any kind of issued ban on a product, so official reasons behind their bans remain unclear. However, bans issued by the NMC apply only to the sale of those products through local outlets; they do not make private ownership illegal. There are certain exceptions, notably for ''[[Spec Ops: The Line]]'' (see below). Some banned games may be available and sold on the nation's [[grey market]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\nIn 2018, the NMC introduced a localised rating system for various media, including video games.<ref name=\"NMCratings\">{{cite web |last=Salama |first=Samir |url=https://gulfnews.com/news/uae/media/new-uae-ratings-system-for-films-games-books-1.2176427 |title=New UAE ratings system for films, games, books |work=[[Gulf News]] |date=2018-02-20 |accessdate=2018-05-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521021047/https://gulfnews.com/news/uae/media/new-uae-ratings-system-for-films-games-books-1.2176427 |archive-date=2018-05-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe following <!-- incomplete list --> titles are banned from mainstream physical retail.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Reason\n|-\n| ''[[BlazBlue: Continuum Shift]]''\n| Banned likely due to suggestive and revealing outfits on some characters.<ref>{{cite web\n |publisher    = gamesradar\n |url          = http://www.gamesradar.com/blazblue-continuum-shift-banned-in-united-arab-emirates/\n |title        = BlazBlue: Continuum Shift banned in United Arab Emirates\n |last         = Nagata\n |first        = Tyler\n |date         = 1 February 2011\n |accessdate   = 2012-08-06\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20151009084303/http://www.gamesradar.com/blazblue-continuum-shift-banned-in-united-arab-emirates/\n |archive-date = 2015-10-09\n |url-status   = live\n}}</ref> However, the ban did not extend to digital versions of the game.\n|-\n| ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2]]''\n| This game was banned after players in the GCC noticed that the picture frames in some maps had quotations from the Qur'an, which were very offensive to Muslims.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} The ban was lifted after the developers removed the text on the frames.\n|-\n| ''[[Darksiders]]''\n| Banned likely due to contradicting with customs and traditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/37056/UAE-Darksiders-bannedrnrnUAE-Darksiders-bannedrn|title=UAE: Darksiders banned|access-date=2010-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113153445/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/37056/UAE-Darksiders-bannedrnrnUAE-Darksiders-bannedrn|archive-date=2010-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the ban did not extend to the digital version of the game. Its sequel, ''[[Darksiders II]]'', which features similar themes, was released without issues, and even had a localised print release for the PlayStation 3 version.\n|-\n| ''[[Dead Island]]'' and ''[[Dead Island: Riptide]]''\n| Both banned likely due to \"extreme depictions of violence and scantily-clad game characters\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itp.net/586074-dead-island-banned-in-the-uae|title=Dead Island banned|access-date=2011-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910014706/http://www.itp.net/586074-dead-island-banned-in-the-uae|archive-date=2011-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the ban did not extend to digital versions of the games.\n|-\n| ''[[Dead Rising 2]]''\n| Banned likely due to violence, gambling, and nudity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=491026752624&id=27495087624|title=Official Geekay Games (U.A.E.'s biggest video game retailer) Facebook page stating ''Dead Rising 2'' is banned in the U.A.E.|access-date=2018-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602224339/https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=491026752624&id=27495087624|archive-date=2017-06-02|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban has since been lifted for newer prints of the game.\n|-\n| ''[[Dragon Age: Origins]]''\n| Banned likely due to sexual themes, including possible homosexual relationships.<ref name=\"ME2&DA:O Banned\">{{cite web|url=http://tbreak.com/megamers/7311/news/mass-effect-2-now-banned-in-the-uae.html|title=Mass Effect 2 and Dragon Age: Origins now banned in the UAE|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811001919/http://tbreak.com/megamers/7311/news/mass-effect-2-now-banned-in-the-uae.html|archivedate=2010-08-11}}</ref> The ban has since been lifted for the digital versions of the game.\n|-\n| ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]''\n| Banned likely due to gambling and sexual themes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=10150093681037625&id=27495087624|title=Official Geekay Games (U.A.E.'s biggest video game retailer) Facebook page stating ''Fallout: New Vegas'' is banned in the U.A.E.|access-date